Reference-contexts: 1 Introduction Simulation techniques based on Markov chains are increasingly being popular for Monte Carlo inference under the Bayesian paradigm. Accessible discussions are found for example in Gelfand and Smith (1990), Smith and Roberts (1993), Gilks et al. (1996). The self regenerative (SR) algorithm is one such MCMC technique <ref> (Sahu and Zhigljavsky, 1998) </ref> available for Bayesian computation. These modern computing techniques enable the practicing statistician fit complex statistical models for plausible explanation of data. However, as the data sets and the models become more challenging the 1 limitations of the computation methods (e.g., slow mixing) become more transparent. <p> Also there is no need to monitor convergence diagnostics very much required for the other MCMC techniques. The SR algorithm diagnoses itself. A properly implemented SR algorithm should accept often and should not have high weights (~ n ) for particular points. As shown in this article <ref> (and in a concurrent paper, Sahu and Zhigljavsky, 1998) </ref> the SR algorithm lends itself to easily implemented adaptation. Because of the complexity of the statistical models it is perhaps not possible to start with a proposal density which is close to the target posterior density.
